      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my effect size looks pretty decent but my p-value is 0.06. can u explain why this is technically \"not significant\" even if there's a clear trend in the data? also i feel like there's just so much noise in the sample making it hard to see the actual signal.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, even with a decent effect size, is not significant because, by the strict rules of the statistical $\\text{t}$-test or whatever you're using, you haven't quite crossed the threshold of the predetermined significance level, which is usually $\\alpha = 0.05$. Think of it like this: you've got a small, slightly wobbly pile of pebbles, and you're trying to see if one pile is *definitely* bigger than another. The effect size tells you the difference is real, but the p-value is the measurement of how likely you are to see that difference *if there was actually no difference* in the real world.\n\nIf your p-value is 0.06, it means there's a 6% chance you'd see this result just by random chance, which is slightly higher than the 5% risk you're willing to accept for a false alarm. The noise in your sample, you say? That's the *standard deviation* doing its dirty work, making the signal look fuzzy.\n\nIt's a real pain, but don't let the little noise scare you.",
      "source": "target",
